1. Principles of Testing

Software testing follows certain basic principles that help testers perform testing effectively and avoid mistakes.
1. Testing Shows Presence of Defects
   Testing helps us find bugs in software, but it cannot guarantee that software has zero defects.
   Example:
        Even after testing a mobile app many times, a new bug may appear later.
        Meaning: Testing reduces risk, not removes it completely.

2. Exhaustive Testing is Impossible
Testing every input, every combination, and every scenario is impossible because software can have thousands or millions of possibilities.
Example:
     Password field with 8 characters can have millions of combinations.
     So testers test important and risky areas instead of everything.

3. Early Testing Saves Time and Cost
Finding defects early (requirement/design phase) is cheaper than fixing them after release.
Example:
     Requirement phase fix → minutes
     Production bug fix → days + customer impact

4. Defect Clustering
Most defects are usually found in a small part of the application.
Example:
    Login module may contain more bugs than other pages.
    This is also called 80/20 rule:
                 80% bugs exist in 20% modules.

5. Pesticide Paradox
Running the same test cases again and again will stop finding new bugs.
Solution:
✔ Update test cases
✔ Add new scenarios

6. Testing Depends on Context
Testing approach changes based on application type.
Examples:
        Banking app → Security testing important
        Gaming app → Performance & usability important

7. Absence of Errors Fallacy
Software without bugs is useless if it does not meet user needs.
Example:
     App works perfectly but customer requirement is wrong.
